          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">
          Israel‚Äôs changing political landscape </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: As Israel's conflict in Gaza intensifies, Israelis are publicly opposing the war. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          As Israel‚Äôs war in Gaza escalates, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-spotlight-h2-3-dissent-at-home" target="_blank">dissent at home</a> is rising, and public opinion is changing. Most people want to end the war and secure a hostage agreement. The mood among others in Israeli society "is one of despair, trauma, and a lack of a sense of ability to change anything." Anti-war protests, led by groups like Standing Together, are growing despite arrests. Many IDF reservists have signed letters urging a ceasefire.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Former IDF deputy commander Yair Golan and ex-Defense Minister Moshe Ya'alon have criticized the government‚Äôs actions. They warn of a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-spotlight-h2-4-moral-and-strategic-collapse" target="_blank">moral and strategic collapse</a>. Golan compared Israel's path to apartheid-era South Africa, which angered PM Netanyahu, who labeled Golan‚Äôs remarks a ‚Äúblood libel.‚Äù Ya'alon took it further, claiming the government is using the war to cling to power.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         However, there are still loud voices within Israeli society that do support the war in Gaza. As Israeli society faces trauma and political gridlock, calls for a change in strategy are becoming stronger. This also includes international pressure, where countries traditionally aligned with Israel, including the UK, France, and Canada, jointly condemned Israel‚Äôs actions.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
