          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
        The Gulf States and the Balkans
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: The EU faces tougher competition for influence from actors such as the UAE in the Balkans.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The Montenegro-UAE development agreement <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-analysis-h1-5-shows-a-growing-challenge" target="_blank">shows a growing challenge</a> for the EU in the Western Balkans. Countries like China, Russia, and the UAE invest quickly to gain influence. Meanwhile, the EU‚Äôs slower, rules-based approach is falling behind. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Montenegro‚Äôs leaders initially welcomed the UAE's proposed $33-39B tourism project in Velika Pla≈æa. Later, the plan received a lot of public backlash due to its vague details, environmental risks, and lack of democratic input. Local communities, civil society groups, and regional leaders were excluded, and the process had minimal transparency. The opposition to the UAE agreement was not against capital funding. It was for putting democratic accountability and local empowerment. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          If the EU does not hurry, it risks losing credibility and influence. The EU can boost its institutional resilience by supporting a community-driven development model that matches Montenegro‚Äôs principles. Velika Pla≈æa, which is ecologically vital and culturally rich, could become a pilot site for EU-led ecotourism and participatory planning initiatives, demonstrating the value of EU membership.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The situation highlights the ill effects of ‚Äúcorrosive capital.‚Äù As the Montenegrin parliament will hold its final vote on the agreement on May 29, the EU needs to move swiftly before someone else builds the future in its place. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
