          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-top:4px;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üá¨üáß UK - Chagos handover.</strong> After a last-minute court injunction was lifted, the UK cleared its Chagos Islands handover to Mauritius. PM Keir Starmer supports the move, despite concerns over Mauritius‚Äôs China ties. Critics argue the agreement risks national security and bypasses proper consultation with islanders. The agreement marks a significant step in ending Britain‚Äôs colonial legacy in the Indian Ocean (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-worldwide-6-more-about-the-agreement" target="_blank">more about the agreement</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üá´üáÆ Finland - Fence with Russia.</strong>   Finland has built 35 km of a planned 200 km border fence with Russia. This 4.5-metre-high fence aims to halt migrant crossings. A surge of asylum seekers in 2023, which Finland asserts is linked to Moscow, prompted the construction. It features barbed wire, cameras, and sensors. Russia denies any involvement. However, Finland sees the fence as vital for national security, despite criticism from human rights groups (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-worldwide-7-borders-secured" target="_blank">border secured</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üáµüá± Poland - Assassination plot.</strong> Polish prosecutors have indicted a man for helping Russian intelligence plan an assassination of Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy. Reports say he agreed to work with Russian military intelligence and gathered details on security at Rzesz√≥w-Jasionka Airport. This airport is a key hub for Western aid to Ukraine. He could face up to eight years in prison (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-worldwide-8-the-plot" target="_blank">the plot</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üáµüá≠ Philippines - Drills with the US.</strong> The US and Philippine militaries conducted joint drills in the Sulu Sea, near the disputed South China Sea, amid rising tensions with China. The exercises focused on maritime awareness, tactics, and search operations. Despite a 2016 ruling rejecting Beijing‚Äôs assertions, China maintains military bases on contested reefs. The US reaffirms its defense commitment to the Philippines (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-worldwide-9-more-about-the-dispute" target="_blank">more about the dispute</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;padding-bottom:6px;">
           <strong>üá∫üá≤ US - Israeli diplomats murdered.</strong> 
            Two Israeli embassy staff were shot outside the Capital Jewish Museum in Washington, DC. The suspect, Elias Rodriguez, was arrested on the spot. He shouted pro-Palestine slogans during the incident. Officials called the attack antisemitic, and there is an ongoing investigation (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-worldwide-10-the-case" target="_blank">the case</a>).
          </p>
