</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/legal-tools-freeze-foreign-assets.png" alt="Legal instruments empower governments to block access to foreign states or entities' financial resources" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>Judicial instruments empower governments to block the gateway to foreign states or entities' monetary resources. Credits: United Nations</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        Countries mainly freeze assets from other countries through sanctions. These are judicial and diplomatic tools to apply pressure or respond to actions that violate international norms. Asset freezes can target government entities, state-owned enterprises, officials, or individuals linked to a regime.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      A country will enlist help from international bodies like the United Nations or the European Union to enforce asset freezes. For example, the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-may-25-foundations-h1-11-un-security-council" target="_blank">UN Security Council</a> can pass resolutions requiring member states to freeze the assets of countries or leaders involved in terrorism, nuclear proliferation, or aggression.</p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
    Countries enforce asset freezes through monetary intelligence units, central banks, or treasury departments. Banks and monetary institutions must locate and block accounts or transactions connected to the targeted state, organization, or individual.</p>
     <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
    Freezing assets may involve foreign reserves in central banks, funds, or property overseas. For example, during conflicts, the US has frozen billions in assets owned by Iran, Venezuela, or Russia. These actions usually depend on national laws, often citing foreign policy or national security. However, these actions face obstacles under international law, particularly if viewed as unilateral or politically motivated. </p>
       </mj-text>
